{"title_page": "Wenatchee child abuse prosecutions", "text_new": "The '''Wenatchee child abuse prosecutions''' in [[Wenatchee, Washington]], US, occurred in 1994 and 1995, at the end of the [[hysteria over child molestation in the 1980s]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB835224586731818500 |title = Wenatchee Update|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 7 October 1995}}</ref>  Many poor and intellectually disabled suspects pled guilty, while those who hired private lawyers were acquitted.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |first= Timothy|last= Egan|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Pastor and Wife Are Acquitted on All Charges in Sex-Abuse Case.|quote=After less than a day of deliberation, a jury today acquitted a lay pastor and his wife of all charges of sexual abuse of children in a trial that critics say demonstrated the worst aspects of police misconduct in such cases. The defendants, Robert and Connie Roberson, were accused of being at the center of a sex ring in which children were ritualistically raped and abused. ... Prosecutors offered no physical evidence to support the charges. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/12/us/pastor-and-wife-are-acquitted-on-all-charges-in-sex-abuse-case.html |work=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=2007-10-31 | date=December 12, 1995}}</ref><ref name=doug/><ref name=ipt/>  Eventually all those accused in these cases were released,<ref name=pul/> and the authorities paid damages to some of those originally accused.<ref name=st09/><ref name=ww07/>\n\n==Accusations==\n\nThe investigation began in January 1995 when Detective Robert Perez was told by his 13-year-old [[Foster care|foster daughter]], Donna Perez, that she had been sexually molested. On March 13, 1995, Perez put Donna in his police car with two social services caseworkers and they drove through Wenatchee and East Wenatchee. Donna pointed out houses and buildings where she says she and other children were repeatedly raped and molested since January 1988. She listed 22 locations.<ref name=spi03>{{cite news |first=ANDREW |last=SCHNEIDER |first2=MIKE |last2=BARBER |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Children sacrificed for the case: Allegations set up a puzzle of doubtful ethics, dubious facts |url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=535 | publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= February 23, 1998 |quote=On the morning of March 13, 1995, Perez put Donna in the front seat of his police car. Two CPS caseworkers were in the back taking notes as they drove through Wenatchee and East Wenatchee. Donna pointed out houses and buildings where she says she and other children were repeatedly raped and molested since January 1988 -- 22 places in all. Along the way she saw a delivery man and a taxi driver. They were added to the list.\"|accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031004193153/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/history.html |archivedate=2003-10-04}}</ref>\n\nMany of the people convicted were poor, had intellectual disabilities and were on [[Administration of federal assistance in the United States|welfare]], and their lawyers stated that their guilty pleas were coerced. In 1995, after Pastor Robert Roberson criticized the investigation, he was arrested and charged with eleven counts of the sexual abuse of a child. Roberson and his wife were acquitted of all charges.<ref name=\"New York Times\"/><ref name=cnn>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9512/sex_ring/ |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20000903082937/http://www.cnn.com/US/9512/sex_ring/|archive-date = 2000-09-03|title = CNN - Pastor, wife acquitted in child sex trial - Dec. 12, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests==\nForty-three adults were arrested on 29,726 charges of child sex abuse, involving 60 children in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=A record of abuses in Wenatchee. |url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=535 |publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |quote=The town of Wenatchee, Washington, made world headlines in 1994 and 1995 when police and state social workers undertook what was then called the nation's most extensive child sex-abuse investigation.|accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031203182345/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/ |archivedate=2003-12-03 }}</ref> Parents and Sunday school teachers were charged, and many were convicted of abusing children, often including their own, or their foster children.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB835224113853772000 |title = Wenatchee: A True Story|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 1995-09-26|last1 = Rabinowitz|first1 = Dorothy |authorlink=Dorothy Rabinowitz |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030821134950/http://www.opinionjournal.com/extra/?id=95000905 |archivedate=2003-08-21 }}</ref>  \nSeveral of the accused claimed that their confessions were coerced.  \"None of the interviews, or the adults' confessions, was taped\",<ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950608&slug=2125346 |title = The Unraveling of a Monstrous Secret -- Sex-Abuse Scandal Has Wenatchee Reeling &#124; the Seattle Times}}</ref> nor did Perez take notes.<ref name=ipt>{{cite web | url=http://www.ipt-forensics.com/journal/volume10/j10_br20.htm |journal= IPT Journal |title =Book Review - 'Witch Hunt: A True Story of Social Hysteria and Abused Justice' |first=LeRoy G. |last=Schultz |year=1998}}</ref>  Sixteen adults entered [[Alford plea]]s; most of these were poor or \"functionally retarded\".<ref name=sm95>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1995/oct/22/sex-case-a-wenatchee-witch-hunt-some-incidents-of/ | title=Sex Case A 'Wenatchee Witch Hunt' Some Incidents of Incest Were Uncovered but There's Been No Proof of Group Child Abuse |publisher= [[Spokesman-Review]] |date= October 22, 1995 |first=J. Todd |last=Foster}}</ref>\n\n==Trials==\nProsecutors were unable to provide any physical evidence to support the charges against the Robersons. The main witness was Perez' foster daughter; Perez was the investigator of the cases.<ref name=\"New York Times\"/>  A juror reported that acquitting the Robersons \"was not a difficult decision for us.\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB835224350133754000 |title = Verdict in Wenatchee|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 16 December 1995|last1 = Rabinowitz|first1 = Dorothy}}</ref>  A jury also acquitted Honnah Sims; one of the jurors criticized the lack of evidence and described the case as \"a witch hunt\".<ref name=sm95/> Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability filed a complaint with the state Commission on Judicial Conduct criticizing judges T.W. \u201cChip\u201d Small (judge in the Roberson case) and Carol Wardell (judge in earlier cases) with professional misconduct.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www2.spokesman.com/stories/1996/apr/16/judges-targeted-in-sex-ring-case/ |title = Judges Targeted in Sex Ring Case &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>\n\n==Conviction review summary==\nThis case was mishandled by the police. Proper protocol was not followed when interviewing the children. Because of this, those who were convicted were freed by higher courts and had their convictions overturned or pleaded guilty on lesser charges. Five served their full sentences before their cases were overturned. Some lost parental rights. By 2000, the last person in custody, Michael Rose, was released, after a judge vacated his March 1995 convictions.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Last child-sex ring defendant released from prison after court action. |url=http://seattlepi.com/local/wena27ww.shtml | publisher = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= December 27, 2000|quote=When he got out of prison, Michael Rose hugged his mother and just felt relieved that the ordeal of child-sex ring prosecution was over. |accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031222021057/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/local/wena27ww.shtml |archivedate=2003-12-22 }}</ref>\n\n[[U.S. Attorney General]] [[Janet Reno]] declined to involve the national Justice Department in these cases.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB846454858888293000 |title = The Pursuit of Justice in Dade County|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 1996-10-28|last1 = Rabinowitz|first1 = Dorothy |authorlink=Dorothy Rabinowitz |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030803074347/http://www.psych.mcgill.ca/courses/xcourses/oct29.htm |archivedate=2003-08-03}}</ref>  The FBI did not question anyone; instead they shipped Reno documents which she found \"do not present evidence of prosecutable violations of federal civil rights law.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Justice's watchdogs looked the other way: An angry reaction |url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=553 | publisher = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= February 27, 1998  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040206195509/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/probe2.html |archivedate=2004-02-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Culpability==\nIn 1996, a consultant, retired Bellevue Police Chief D.P. Van Blaricom, hired by a city insurer who looked into how the Wenatchee police ran the child abuse investigations, stated that the cases were handled properly.  In 1998, Phillip Esplin, a forensic psychologist for the [[National Institutes of Health]]'s Child Witness Project said that \"Wenatchee may be the worst example ever of mental health services being abused by a state ... to control and manage children who have been frightened and coerced into falsely accusing their parents and neighbors of the most heinous of crimes.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Wenatchee abuses attacked nationally. |url=http://seattlepi.com/powertoharm/after13.html |publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=May 28, 1998 |quote=The Wenatchee child sex-abuse investigations are the nation's most blatant example of continuing judicial abuse, civil libertarians and nationally known commentators said at a conference here yesterday. |accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040920085807/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/after13.html |archivedate=2004-09-20 }}</ref> In 2001, a jury found the city of [[Wenatchee]] and [[Douglas County, Washington]] negligent in the 1994-1995 investigations. They awarded $3 million to a couple who had been wrongly accused in the inquiry,<ref name=doug>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Jury finds city, county negligent in child sex ring case. |url = http://seattlepi.com/local/33472_wenatchee01.shtml | publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= August 1, 2001 |accessdate=2007-11-26 |first1=Mike |last1=Barber |first2=Larry |last2=Lange}}</ref> but the state supreme court later upheld an appeals court ruling reducing this award to the Sims.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated |first=The |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/justices-reject-sex-ring-case-award/article_b62fcdee-763e-53af-ab30-fd689ae06d8c.html |title=Justices reject sex-ring case award - &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nRobert Perez was the sex-crimes investigator despite having been arrested, involvement in a child custody dispute,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=536 | title=Part I, b - Detective a man who charmed, harmed}}</ref>  and a 1989 performance evaluation that said he \"likes confrontation and likes having power over people\".<ref name=sm95/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.aol.com/cclawa/pages/perez.htm |title=Robert Perez Police Department Evaluation|date=February 24, 1989 |publisher=Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010630124228/http://www.ags.uci.edu/~dehill/witchhunt/ccla/pages/perez.htm|archive-date=2001-06-30}}</ref>  But the [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] argued that while Perez got a lot of the criticism, \"he was just the point man for an investigation either directed by or undertaken with the active involvement of CPS officials.\"<ref name=spi03/>  Perez died in 2013 at age 60.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.seattletimes.com/news/ex-wenatchee-sex-crime-detective-bob-perez-dies/ |title = Ex-Wenatchee sex crime detective Bob Perez dies|date = 2013-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jefferson Robbins |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/bob-perez-driving-force-in-discredited-sex-abuse-cases-dies/article_0425db16-0a82-562c-a51d-f8d00b162aa8.html |title=Bob Perez, driving force in discredited sex abuse cases, dies &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date=2013-12-18 |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Pierce County]] public defender Kathryn Lyon compiled \"The Wenatchee Report\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.aol.com/cclawa/pages/lyon.htm |title=Kathryn Lyon's Wenatchee Reports |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010630121826/http://www.ags.uci.edu/~dehill/witchhunt/ccla/pages/lyon.htm |accessdate=2020-05-02|archive-date=2001-06-30  |publisher=Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability}}</ref> which \"purport[ed] to show civil-rights violations involving children and families in Chelan and Douglas counties.\"<ref name=alb>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/mar/28/author-fights-sex-ring-case-subpoena/ |title = Author Fights Sex-Ring Case Subpoena &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>  Perez attempted to subpoena Lyon's sources,<ref name=alb/> but was unsuccessful, except for a tape that Lyon had already shared with others.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/apr/02/writer-need-not-reveal-sources-in-wenatchee-sex/ |title = Writer Need Not Reveal Sources in Wenatchee Sex-Ring Cases &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>  This work formed the basis of Lyon's 1998 book, ''Witch Hunt: A True Story of Social Hysteria and Abused Justice''.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press |url=https://lmtribune.com/northwest/child-sex-ring-book-gets-mixed-reviews/article_a9c0e98c-1104-5ff8-815b-4c4b07369037.html |title=Child sex ring book gets mixed reviews &#124; Northwest |publisher=lmtribune.com |date=1998-02-20 |accessdate=2020-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19980303&slug=2737443 |title = One Brave Soul's Crusade for Truth About Wenatchee &#124; the Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nCourts have freed all those once imprisoned in these prosecutions.  Carol and Mark Doggett were freed,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19971210&slug=2577243 |title = Wenatchee Couple's Rape Conviction is Overturned &#124; the Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://casetext.com/case/state-v-carol-md | title=State v. Carol M.D, 89 Wn. App. 77 &#124; Casetext Search + Citator}}</ref> but then still required legal assistance to get their children returned to their custody.<ref name=pul>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/dorothy-rabinowitz |title=Afterward: Freedom is never the same for those who've been to prison on phony chages |publisher=Pulitzer.org |date=December 29, 2000 |archivedate=2004-12-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041218020757/http://www.opinionjournal.com/extra/?id=90000450 }}</ref>\n\nThose once accused filed lawsuits against the authorities who once prosecuted them.<ref name=ww07>{{cite web|url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/roberson-v/article_cb3e53ca-24c0-512e-be81-568cf9b39634.html |title=Roberson v. ... &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>  The city of Wenatchee paid the Robersons a settlement of $700,000.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jaime Adame |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/city-s-sex-case-settlement-with-roberson/article_ce7a36b7-ac0f-5773-a11a-eba9663d301e.html |title=City's sex-case settlement with Roberson: $700,000 &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>  After their acquittal for child abuse, the Robersons were prosecuted for earlier welfare fraud, for which Robert [[plea-bargain]]ed to [[community service]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/jul/12/roberson-says-hes-due-credit-pastor-wants-talks/ |title = Roberson Says He's Due Credit Pastor Wants Talks with Media Counted as Community Service &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/jul/13/sex-ring-defendant-cant-just-do-pr-work-state/ |title = Sex-Ring Defendant Can't Just do Pr Work, State Says Roberson Must Come up with Better Plan for Community Service Work &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>  The last lawsuit against the authorities in these cases was settled in 2009, with the children of Harold and Idella Everett, who initially pled guilty, receiving $120,000.<ref name=st09>{{cite web | url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/last-case-settled-in-botched-sex-ring-case/ |title = Last case settled in botched sex ring case|date = 2009-05-25 |publisher=Seattle Times |archiveurl=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=1254 |archivedate=2018-09-14}}</ref>  Manuel Hidalgo Rodriguez, convicted in 1995,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB937867571484668143 |title = Reckoning in Wenatchee|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 21 September 1999}}</ref> won $689,000 from his former defense lawyers.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jefferson Robbins |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/lesser-settlement-stands-in-sex-abuse-civil-case/article_6da6f183-ad1c-548a-9c94-378a796a6081.html |title=Lesser settlement stands in sex-abuse civil case &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Pastor Roby and Connie Roberson attended the \"Day of Contrition\" conference in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], along with other victims and experts of the [[day-care sex-abuse hysteria]].<ref name=ipt/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://culteducation.com/group/1138-satanism/18251-protesting-modern-witchunts.html|title=Protesting Modern Witchunts|website=culteducation.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fmsfonline.org/newsletters/fmsf_1997_feb_v6_n2.html|title=FMSF Newsletter - February 1, 1997 - Vol. 6, No. 2|website=www.fmsfonline.org}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Day care sex abuse hysteria]]\n* [[McMartin preschool trial]]\n* [[Moral panic]]\n* [[Satanic ritual abuse]]\n* [[Witch-hunt]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=7065 Wenatchee Witch Hunt: Child Sex Abuse Trials In Douglas and Chelan Counties] [[HistoryLink]] Essay 7065\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010101/http://members.aol.com/cclawa Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100613102443/http://www.truthinjustice.org/victims-fury.htm Victims of the Fury]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20031203182345/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/ The Power to Harm] series from the [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n* {{cite book |last=Lyon |first=Kathryn |title=Witch Hunt: A True Story of Social Hysteria and Abused Justice |year=1998 |publisher=[[Avon Books]] |isbn=978-0-380-79066-1 |oclc=38482904 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=o4L-GwAACAAJ}}\n\n[[Category:Day care sexual abuse allegations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sex scandals]]\n[[Category:1994 in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1995 in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:History of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Wenatchee, Washington]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Wenatchee child abuse prosecutions''' in [[Wenatchee, Washington]], US, occurred in 1994 and 1995, at the end of the [[hysteria over child molestation in the 1980s]].<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB835224586731818500 |title = Wenatchee Update|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 7 October 1995}}</ref>  Many poor and intellectually disabled suspects pled guilty, while those who hired private lawyers were acquitted.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news |first= Timothy|last= Egan|authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Pastor and Wife Are Acquitted on All Charges in Sex-Abuse Case.|quote=After less than a day of deliberation, a jury today acquitted a lay pastor and his wife of all charges of sexual abuse of children in a trial that critics say demonstrated the worst aspects of police misconduct in such cases. The defendants, Robert and Connie Roberson, were accused of being at the center of a sex ring in which children were ritualistically raped and abused. ... Prosecutors offered no physical evidence to support the charges. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/12/us/pastor-and-wife-are-acquitted-on-all-charges-in-sex-abuse-case.html |work=[[New York Times]] |accessdate=2007-10-31 | date=December 12, 1995}}</ref><ref name=doug/><ref name=ipt/>  Eventually all those accused in these cases were released,<ref name=pul/> and the authorities paid damages to some of those originally accused.<ref name=st09/><ref name=ww07/>\n\n==Accusations==\n\nThe investigation began in January 1995 when Detective Robert Perez was told by his 13-year-old [[Foster care|foster daughter]], Donna Perez, that she had been sexually molested. On March 13, 1995, Perez put Donna in his police car with two social services caseworkers and they drove through Wenatchee and East Wenatchee. Donna pointed out houses and buildings where she says she and other children were repeatedly raped and molested since January 1988. She listed 22 locations.<ref name=spi03>{{cite news |first=ANDREW |last=SCHNEIDER |first2=MIKE |last2=BARBER |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Children sacrificed for the case: Allegations set up a puzzle of doubtful ethics, dubious facts |url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=535 | publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= February 23, 1998 |quote=On the morning of March 13, 1995, Perez put Donna in the front seat of his police car. Two CPS caseworkers were in the back taking notes as they drove through Wenatchee and East Wenatchee. Donna pointed out houses and buildings where she says she and other children were repeatedly raped and molested since January 1988 -- 22 places in all. Along the way she saw a delivery man and a taxi driver. They were added to the list.\"|accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031004193153/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/history.html |archivedate=2003-10-04}}</ref>\n\nMany of the people convicted were poor, had intellectual disabilities and were on [[Administration of federal assistance in the United States|welfare]], and their lawyers stated that their guilty pleas were coerced. In 1995, after Pastor Robert Roberson criticized the investigation, he was arrested and charged with eleven counts of the sexual abuse of a child. Roberson and his wife were acquitted of all charges.<ref name=\"New York Times\"/><ref name=cnn>{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9512/sex_ring/ |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20000903082937/http://www.cnn.com/US/9512/sex_ring/|archive-date = 2000-09-03|title = CNN - Pastor, wife acquitted in child sex trial - Dec. 12, 1995}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests==\nForty-three adults were arrested on 29,726 charges of child sex abuse, involving 60 children in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=A record of abuses in Wenatchee. |url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=535 |publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |quote=The town of Wenatchee, Washington, made world headlines in 1994 and 1995 when police and state social workers undertook what was then called the nation's most extensive child sex-abuse investigation.|accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031203182345/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/ |archivedate=2003-12-03 }}</ref> Parents and Sunday school teachers were charged, and many were convicted of abusing children, often including their own, or their foster children.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB835224113853772000 |title = Wenatchee: A True Story|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 1995-09-26|last1 = Rabinowitz|first1 = Dorothy |authorlink=Dorothy Rabinowitz |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030821134950/http://www.opinionjournal.com/extra/?id=95000905 |archivedate=2003-08-21 }}</ref>  \nSeveral of the accused claimed that their confessions were coerced.  \"None of the interviews, or the adults' confessions, was taped\",<ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19950608&slug=2125346 |title = The Unraveling of a Monstrous Secret -- Sex-Abuse Scandal Has Wenatchee Reeling &#124; the Seattle Times}}</ref> nor did Perez take notes.<ref name=ipt>{{cite web | url=http://www.ipt-forensics.com/journal/volume10/j10_br20.htm |title = IPT Journal - Book Review - \"Witch Hunt: A True Story of Social Hysteria and Abused Justice\"}}</ref>  Sixteen adults entered [[Alford plea]]s; most of these were poor or \"functionally retarded\".<ref name=sm95>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1995/oct/22/sex-case-a-wenatchee-witch-hunt-some-incidents-of/ | title=Sex Case A 'Wenatchee Witch Hunt' Some Incidents of Incest Were Uncovered but There's Been No Proof of Group Child Abuse |publisher= [[Spokesman-Review]] |date= October 22, 1995 |first=J. Todd |last=Foster}}</ref>\n\n==Trials==\nProsecutors were unable to provide any physical evidence to support the charges against the Robersons. The main witness was Perez' foster daughter; Perez was the investigator of the cases.<ref name=\"New York Times\"/>  A juror reported that acquitting the Robersons \"was not a difficult decision for us.\"<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB835224350133754000 |title = Verdict in Wenatchee|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 16 December 1995|last1 = Rabinowitz|first1 = Dorothy}}</ref>  A jury also acquitted Honnah Sims; one of the jurors criticized the lack of evidence and described the case as \"a witch hunt\".<ref name=sm95/> Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability filed a complaint with the state Commission on Judicial Conduct criticizing judges T.W. \u201cChip\u201d Small (judge in the Roberson case) and Carol Wardell (judge in earlier cases) with professional misconduct.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www2.spokesman.com/stories/1996/apr/16/judges-targeted-in-sex-ring-case/ |title = Judges Targeted in Sex Ring Case &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>\n\n==Conviction review summary==\nThis case was mishandled by the police. Proper protocol was not followed when interviewing the children. Because of this, those who were convicted were freed by higher courts and had their convictions overturned or pleaded guilty on lesser charges. Five served their full sentences before their cases were overturned. Some lost parental rights. By 2000, the last person in custody, Michael Rose, was released, after a judge vacated his March 1995 convictions.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Last child-sex ring defendant released from prison after court action. |url=http://seattlepi.com/local/wena27ww.shtml | publisher = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= December 27, 2000|quote=When he got out of prison, Michael Rose hugged his mother and just felt relieved that the ordeal of child-sex ring prosecution was over. |accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031222021057/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/local/wena27ww.shtml |archivedate=2003-12-22 }}</ref>\n\n[[U.S. Attorney General]] [[Janet Reno]] declined to involve the national Justice Department in these cases.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB846454858888293000 |title = The Pursuit of Justice in Dade County|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 1996-10-28|last1 = Rabinowitz|first1 = Dorothy |authorlink=Dorothy Rabinowitz |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030803074347/http://www.psych.mcgill.ca/courses/xcourses/oct29.htm |archivedate=2003-08-03}}</ref>  The FBI did not question anyone; instead they shipped Reno documents which she found \"do not present evidence of prosecutable violations of federal civil rights law.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Justice's watchdogs looked the other way: An angry reaction |url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=553 | publisher = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= February 27, 1998  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040206195509/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/probe2.html |archivedate=2004-02-06 }}</ref>\n\n==Culpability==\nIn 1996, a consultant, retired Bellevue Police Chief D.P. Van Blaricom, hired by a city insurer who looked into how the Wenatchee police ran the child abuse investigations, stated that the cases were handled properly.  In 1998, Phillip Esplin, a forensic psychologist for the [[National Institutes of Health]]'s Child Witness Project said that \"Wenatchee may be the worst example ever of mental health services being abused by a state ... to control and manage children who have been frightened and coerced into falsely accusing their parents and neighbors of the most heinous of crimes.\"<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Wenatchee abuses attacked nationally. |url=http://seattlepi.com/powertoharm/after13.html |publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=May 28, 1998 |quote=The Wenatchee child sex-abuse investigations are the nation's most blatant example of continuing judicial abuse, civil libertarians and nationally known commentators said at a conference here yesterday. |accessdate=2007-11-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040920085807/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/after13.html |archivedate=2004-09-20 }}</ref> In 2001, a jury found the city of [[Wenatchee]] and [[Douglas County, Washington]] negligent in the 1994-1995 investigations. They awarded $3 million to a couple who had been wrongly accused in the inquiry,<ref name=doug>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Jury finds city, county negligent in child sex ring case. |url = http://seattlepi.com/local/33472_wenatchee01.shtml | publisher=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date= August 1, 2001 |accessdate=2007-11-26 |first1=Mike |last1=Barber |first2=Larry |last2=Lange}}</ref> but the state supreme court later upheld an appeals court ruling reducing this award to the Sims.<ref>{{cite web|last=Associated |first=The |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/justices-reject-sex-ring-case-award/article_b62fcdee-763e-53af-ab30-fd689ae06d8c.html |title=Justices reject sex-ring case award - &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nRobert Perez was the sex-crimes investigator despite having been arrested, involvement in a child custody dispute,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=536 | title=Part I, b - Detective a man who charmed, harmed}}</ref>  and a 1989 performance evaluation that said he \"likes confrontation and likes having power over people\".<ref name=sm95/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.aol.com/cclawa/pages/perez.htm |title=Robert Perez Police Department Evaluation|date=February 24, 1989 |publisher=Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010630124228/http://www.ags.uci.edu/~dehill/witchhunt/ccla/pages/perez.htm|archive-date=2001-06-30}}</ref>  But the [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] argued that while Perez got a lot of the criticism, \"he was just the point man for an investigation either directed by or undertaken with the active involvement of CPS officials.\"<ref name=spi03/>  Perez died in 2013 at age 60.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.seattletimes.com/news/ex-wenatchee-sex-crime-detective-bob-perez-dies/ |title = Ex-Wenatchee sex crime detective Bob Perez dies|date = 2013-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jefferson Robbins |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/bob-perez-driving-force-in-discredited-sex-abuse-cases-dies/article_0425db16-0a82-562c-a51d-f8d00b162aa8.html |title=Bob Perez, driving force in discredited sex abuse cases, dies &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date=2013-12-18 |accessdate=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Pierce County]] public defender Kathryn Lyon compiled \"The Wenatchee Report\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.aol.com/cclawa/pages/lyon.htm |title=Kathryn Lyon's Wenatchee Reports |date= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010630121826/http://www.ags.uci.edu/~dehill/witchhunt/ccla/pages/lyon.htm |accessdate=2020-05-02|archive-date=2001-06-30  |publisher=Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability}}</ref> which \"purport[ed] to show civil-rights violations involving children and families in Chelan and Douglas counties.\"<ref name=alb>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/mar/28/author-fights-sex-ring-case-subpoena/ |title = Author Fights Sex-Ring Case Subpoena &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>  Perez attempted to subpoena Lyon's sources,<ref name=alb/> but was unsuccessful, except for a tape that Lyon had already shared with others.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/apr/02/writer-need-not-reveal-sources-in-wenatchee-sex/ |title = Writer Need Not Reveal Sources in Wenatchee Sex-Ring Cases &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>  This work formed the basis of Lyon's 1998 book, ''Witch Hunt: A True Story of Social Hysteria and Abused Justice''.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press |url=https://lmtribune.com/northwest/child-sex-ring-book-gets-mixed-reviews/article_a9c0e98c-1104-5ff8-815b-4c4b07369037.html |title=Child sex ring book gets mixed reviews &#124; Northwest |publisher=lmtribune.com |date=1998-02-20 |accessdate=2020-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19980303&slug=2737443 |title = One Brave Soul's Crusade for Truth About Wenatchee &#124; the Seattle Times}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nCourts have freed all those once imprisoned in these prosecutions.  Carol and Mark Doggett were freed,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://archive.seattletimes.com/archive/?date=19971210&slug=2577243 |title = Wenatchee Couple's Rape Conviction is Overturned &#124; the Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://casetext.com/case/state-v-carol-md | title=State v. Carol M.D, 89 Wn. App. 77 &#124; Casetext Search + Citator}}</ref> but then still required legal assistance to get their children returned to their custody.<ref name=pul>{{cite web|url=https://www.pulitzer.org/winners/dorothy-rabinowitz |title=Afterward: Freedom is never the same for those who've been to prison on phony chages |publisher=Pulitzer.org |date=December 29, 2000 |archivedate=2004-12-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041218020757/http://www.opinionjournal.com/extra/?id=90000450 }}</ref>\n\nThose once accused filed lawsuits against the authorities who once prosecuted them.<ref name=ww07>{{cite web|url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/roberson-v/article_cb3e53ca-24c0-512e-be81-568cf9b39634.html |title=Roberson v. ... &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>  The city of Wenatchee paid the Robersons a settlement of $700,000.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jaime Adame |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/city-s-sex-case-settlement-with-roberson/article_ce7a36b7-ac0f-5773-a11a-eba9663d301e.html |title=City's sex-case settlement with Roberson: $700,000 &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>  After their acquittal for child abuse, the Robersons were prosecuted for earlier welfare fraud, for which Robert [[plea-bargain]]ed to [[community service]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/jul/12/roberson-says-hes-due-credit-pastor-wants-talks/ |title = Roberson Says He's Due Credit Pastor Wants Talks with Media Counted as Community Service &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/1996/jul/13/sex-ring-defendant-cant-just-do-pr-work-state/ |title = Sex-Ring Defendant Can't Just do Pr Work, State Says Roberson Must Come up with Better Plan for Community Service Work &#124; the Spokesman-Review}}</ref>  The last lawsuit against the authorities in these cases was settled in 2009, with the children of Harold and Idella Everett, who initially pled guilty, receiving $120,000.<ref name=st09>{{cite web | url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/last-case-settled-in-botched-sex-ring-case/ |title = Last case settled in botched sex ring case|date = 2009-05-25 |publisher=Seattle Times |archiveurl=http://www.lawreport.org/ViewStory.aspx?StoryID=1254 |archivedate=2018-09-14}}</ref>  Manuel Hidalgo Rodriguez, convicted in 1995,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB937867571484668143 |title = Reckoning in Wenatchee|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|date = 21 September 1999}}</ref> won $689,000 from his former defense lawyers.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jefferson Robbins |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/local/lesser-settlement-stands-in-sex-abuse-civil-case/article_6da6f183-ad1c-548a-9c94-378a796a6081.html |title=Lesser settlement stands in sex-abuse civil case &#124; Local News |publisher=wenatcheeworld.com |date= |accessdate=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\nIn 1997, Pastor Roby and Connie Roberson attended the \"Day of Contrition\" conference in [[Salem, Massachusetts]], along with other victims and experts of the [[day-care sex-abuse hysteria]].<ref name=ipt/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://culteducation.com/group/1138-satanism/18251-protesting-modern-witchunts.html|title=Protesting Modern Witchunts|website=culteducation.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fmsfonline.org/newsletters/fmsf_1997_feb_v6_n2.html|title=FMSF Newsletter - February 1, 1997 - Vol. 6, No. 2|website=www.fmsfonline.org}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Day care sex abuse hysteria]]\n* [[McMartin preschool trial]]\n* [[Moral panic]]\n* [[Satanic ritual abuse]]\n* [[Witch-hunt]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.historylink.org/essays/output.cfm?file_id=7065 Wenatchee Witch Hunt: Child Sex Abuse Trials In Douglas and Chelan Counties] [[HistoryLink]] Essay 7065\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010101/http://members.aol.com/cclawa Concerned Citizens for Legal Accountability]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100613102443/http://www.truthinjustice.org/victims-fury.htm Victims of the Fury]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20031203182345/http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/powertoharm/ The Power to Harm] series from the [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n* {{cite book |last=Lyon |first=Kathryn |title=Witch Hunt: A True Story of Social Hysteria and Abused Justice |year=1998 |publisher=[[Avon Books]] |isbn=978-0-380-79066-1 |oclc=38482904 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=o4L-GwAACAAJ}}\n\n[[Category:Day care sexual abuse allegations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sex scandals]]\n[[Category:1994 in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:1995 in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:History of Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Wenatchee, Washington]]\n", "name_user": "DougHill", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eArrests:author, year, publisher", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wenatchee_child_abuse_prosecutions"}
